Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt:
Defendant Jute T. Handrick in court with attorney Daniel Francis Snyder.  Jodie L. Bednar appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Also calling 15CF11. Plea questionnaire and waiver filed. State moves to amend Ct. 1 to msd. bail jumping, s. 946.49(1)(a), in 15CF96. Granted by the court. Defendant pleads no contest. State moves to dismiss but read in Ct. 2 in 15CF11. Granted by the court. Defendant pleads no contest.  Court reads on waiver of rights and tendering plea. Waiver free and voluntary. Court finds that a factual basis for the plea exists and finds defendant guilty of Ct. 1 in 15CF96 as amended. Court finds defendant guilty of Ct. 1 in 15CF11 but defers entry. Deferred Entry of Judgment filed/accepted by the Court. Snyder statement to bond conditions--requests no contact provision be lifted. No objection by the State. Court grants motion to amend bond; no contact provision stricken with regards to Andi Hansen only. The court informs defendant of right to request expungement of the DNA under Wis. Stat. 165.77(4). Bond continued as amended by the Court.
